    id: 'counselor-role-national-model', chapterId: 'sc5422-ch-01', domainId: 'define', domain: 'Define',
    label: 'School Counselor Role, Identity, and Program Foundations', references: [ETS, ASCA_PRO, ASCA_PROGRAM],
    questions: [
      q('A principal asks the school counselor to describe the central purpose of a comprehensive school counseling program. Which response is best?', 'At a family orientation, how should a counselor explain the purpose of the school counseling program?', 'It provides planned academic, career, and social/emotional supports that improve access and outcomes for every student.', ['It primarily offers therapy to students with diagnosed mental-health disorders.', 'It exists mainly to complete scheduling and testing paperwork for administrators.', 'It serves only students referred because of severe behavior concerns.'], 'A comprehensive program is preventive, developmental, data informed, and available to all students across academic, career, and social/emotional development.', 'foundation'),
      q('A counselor is assigned to coordinate all standardized testing for three weeks, leaving no time for counseling services. What is the most appropriate response?', 'An administrator asks a counselor to spend most mornings supervising detention instead of delivering the counseling program. What should the counselor do?', 'Use role and time-use data to explain the impact, propose an appropriate staffing solution, and advocate for counseling services.', ['Accept the assignment permanently because administrators define every counselor duty.', 'Refuse publicly without discussing student impact or possible solutions.', 'Cancel only services for students who have not requested individual counseling.'], 'Testing coordination and routine discipline supervision are generally inappropriate noncounseling assignments; advocacy should be collaborative, documented, and centered on student access.'),
      q('Course-failure data show a persistent gap for students entering ninth grade from one feeder school. Which action best demonstrates the counselor as a leader and advocate?', 'Enrollment data show advanced courses underrepresent multilingual students despite comparable prerequisite performance. What is the best counselor response?', 'Disaggregate the data, engage affected students and partners, identify the systemic barrier, and lead a measurable change strategy.', ['Offer encouragement only to students who independently request help.', 'Assume the gap reflects fixed differences in student motivation.', 'Wait until every individual student has failed before discussing the pattern.'], 'Leadership and advocacy use disaggregated evidence and stakeholder voice to remove systemic barriers rather than locating the problem solely within students.'),
      q('A new counselor is aligning lessons to student standards. Which three areas should be represented across the program?', 'A team reviews whether its counseling curriculum is balanced. Which set of student-development areas should guide the review?', 'Academic development, career development, and social/emotional development.', ['Attendance, discipline, and testing administration.', 'Diagnosis, psychotherapy, and medication management.', 'Elementary, middle, and high school scheduling.'], 'The school counseling program addresses academic, career, and social/emotional development; the areas interact and should be supported developmentally.'),
      q('Why is active participation in a school-counseling professional organization useful?', 'A counselor wants to maintain current professional competence. Which activity offers the strongest continuing benefit?', 'It supports access to current standards, research, consultation, advocacy, and continuing professional learning.', ['It transfers ethical responsibility from the counselor to the organization.', 'It replaces the need to follow state credential and district requirements.', 'It guarantees that every shared practice is evidence based.'], 'Professional organizations support learning and connection, but the counselor remains responsible for evaluating evidence and following current law, ethics, credentials, and policy.', 'foundation'),
      q('A schoolwide policy produces repeated discipline disparities. Which action is most consistent with the counselor role?', 'Students report that a course-placement procedure creates an avoidable access barrier. How should the counselor respond?', 'Analyze the pattern with stakeholders and advocate for a fairer policy while monitoring student outcomes.', ['Counsel only individual students to cope with the policy.', 'Publicly identify specific students to make the disparity more persuasive.', 'Avoid the issue because policy change is outside all counseling roles.'], 'School counselors act as leaders, advocates, collaborators, and agents of systemic change while protecting student privacy and using outcome data.'),
      q('A teacher asks the counselor to “fix” a student who withdraws during group work. What is the best initial counselor response?', 'A family asks the counselor to make a teacher change classroom rules for one student. What is the best first step?', 'Clarify the concern, gather contextual information, and collaborate on supports and a way to evaluate them.', ['Promise a specific classroom change before consulting the teacher.', 'Accept sole responsibility for changing the student.', 'Explain that classroom concerns are never part of school counseling.'], 'Consultation is collaborative and data informed. The counselor helps define the concern and coordinate support without taking over another professional’s authority.'),
      q('A counselor notices persistent emotional exhaustion and reduced concentration affecting work. What is the most ethical response?', 'A counselor realizes that stress is impairing judgment in several student situations. What should happen next?', 'Seek supervision or consultation, use wellness supports, and adjust responsibilities as needed to protect competent service.', ['Keep the concern private and continue unchanged until an error occurs.', 'Transfer every student immediately without coordinating continuity.', 'Use student counseling sessions to process the counselor’s stress.'], 'Counselors monitor impairment, seek appropriate support, and protect students. Self-care is an ethical competence practice, not permission to shift personal needs onto students.'),
    ],
